text:
How do neurons communicate with one another?

Your brain has around eighty billion brain cells (neurons)! But how do all of these neurons talk to each other? One way for cells to communicate with one another is by releasing chemicals. This is known as chemical communication.

However, chemical communication is slow. For example, when you release an odor on one side of the room, how long does it take for someone on the edge of the room to smell it? There should be a faster way. One way is to bring cells closer together through stretching.

tiles.title: Neurons need to get closer to each other

text:
But there is still a problem. The signal still needs to travel a long way through the cell. Is there a way to make this faster? What is very fast?

Electricity! Remember how fast the energy stick turned on when you closed the circuit. Neurons use electricity as well; electrical pulses travel down the neurons. This pulse is called an action potential.

Image credit: Backyard Brains.

Program a Light Bulb to Turn On and Off

We can use a computer program to turn lights on and off in the same way you did earlier with the energy sticks.

Here is a very simple program that turns a light bulb on and off based on a timer:

Drag this program to your workspace and modify it in the following way: instead of a timer, use a generator to control the light bulb. To do so, delete the timer and add a generator. Select the "Square" option and add some logic to make the light bulb only turn on when the generated signal is over 0.5.

Watch this brief video tutorial for additional guidance.

Developing a step-by-step solution to problems

To better understand how Tilly's bionic arm works, we need to practice developing step-by-step solutions to problems. As this video demonstrates, this is not always an easy process.

After watching the video, choose an activity you perform every day (for example, brushing your teeth) and write it out step-by-step.

Finally, try to come up with a step-by-step explanation to how Tilly controls how bionic arm.

Reflection

At the end of the activity, please record your current thinking and learning in your Learning journal (see Reflection tab).
